<section class="section methodology" id="methodology">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title fade-in">Scholarly Foundation, Method & Roadmap</h2>

    <div class="methodology-content fade-in">

      <!-- Argument & Scholarly Engagement (Rubric) -->
      <div class="call-to-action-text fade-in" style="margin-bottom:2rem;">
        <h3>Argument & Scholarly Engagement</h3>
        <p style="color:#ccc;line-height:1.7;">
          <strong>Argument:</strong> Guinean cultural memory is at risk of loss; communities must
          <em>own the description, access, and meaning</em> of their materials. This project builds on the
          <strong>work and legacy of Djibril Tamsir Niane</strong> (oral traditions, Manding epic, field recordings)
          to treat <em>oral history as core archival evidence</em> and to link family archives with national memory.
        </p>
        <p style="color:#ccc;line-height:1.7;">
          <strong>Scholarly conversation (4+ sources):</strong> Caswell (community archives & symbolic annihilation),
          Drake (liberatory archives & power), Mbembe (archive/power), Hirsch (postmemory), Trouillot (silences in history),
          and Niane (Manding oral tradition) inform both <em>method</em> (community‑controlled metadata, multilingual description)
